{"title_page": "Gje", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=February 2007}}\n{{For|the European wine classification organisation|Grand Jury Europ\u00e9en}}\n{{Cyrillic alphabet navbox\n|Heading=Cyrillic letter Gje\n|Image=Cyrillic letter Gje - uppercase and lowercase.svg\n|size=100px\n|uuc=0403\n|ulc=0453\n|sound = {{IPA|[\u025f]}}, {{IPA|[d\u0291]}}\n}}\n'''Gje''' (\u0403&nbsp;\u0453; italics: <span style=\"font-family: times, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-size: larger\">''\u0403''&nbsp;''\u0453''</span>) is a letter of the [[Cyrillic script]].\n\n\u0403 is used in [[Macedonian language|Macedonian]] to represent the [[voiced palatal plosive]] {{IPA|/\u025f/}}.\n\n\u0403 is most commonly romanized using the Latin letter G with [[Acute accent|acute]] {{angbr|\u01f5}}. When the [[Socialist Republic of Macedonia]] was part of [[SFR Yugoslavia]], the Macedonian '''\u0453''' was also transliterated as '''\u0111''' or '''dj'''.\n\nWords with this letter are often cognate with {{lang|bg|\u0416\u0434&nbsp;\u0436\u0434}} (''Zhd / zhd'') in [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] and {{lang|sh|{{lang|sh-Cyrl|[[Dje|\u0402&nbsp;\u0452]]}} / {{lang|sh-Latn|[[D with stroke|\u0110&nbsp;\u0111]]}}}}) in [[Serbo-Croatian]]. For example, the Macedonian word for ''birth'' ({{lang|mk|\u0440\u0430\u0453\u0430\u045a\u0435}} is ''ra\u01f5anje'', which in Bulgarian is {{lang|bg|\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0435}} - ''razhdane'', and in Serbian {{lang|sr|\u0440\u0430\u0452\u0430\u045a\u0435}} - ''ra\u0111anje'').\n\n==Related letters and other similar characters==\n*\u0413 \u0433: [[Ge (Cyrillic)|Cyrillic letter Ge]]\n*\u0402 \u0452: [[Dje|Cyrillic letter Dje]]\n*\u040c \u045c: [[Kje|Cyrillic letter Kje]]\n\n{{anchor|Encodings}}\n\n==Computing codes==\n\n{{charmap\n|0403|name1=Cyrillic Capital Letter Gje\n|0453|name2=Cyrillic Small Letter Gje\n|map1=[[Code page 855]] |map1char1=83 |map1char2=82\n|map2=[[Windows-1251]] |map2char1=81 |map2char2=83\n|map3=[[ISO-8859-5]] |map3char1=A3 |map3char2=F3\n|map4=[[Macintosh Cyrillic encoding|Macintosh Cyrillic]] |map4char1=AE |map4char2=AF\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Wiktionary-inline|\u0403}}\n*{{Wiktionary-inline|\u0453}}\n\n\n{{Cyrillic-alphabet-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=February 2007}}\n{{For|the European wine classification organisation|Grand Jury Europ\u00e9en}}\n{{Cyrillic alphabet navbox\n|Heading=Cyrillic letter Gje\n|Image=Cyrillic letter Gje - uppercase and lowercase.svg\n|size=100px\n|uuc=0403\n|ulc=0453\n|sound = {{IPA|[\u025f]}}, {{IPA|[d\u0291]}}\n}}\n'''Gje''' (\u0403&nbsp;\u0453; italics: <span style=\"font-family: times, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-size: larger\">''\u0403''&nbsp;''\u0453''</span>) is a letter of the [[Cyrillic script]].\n\n\u0403 is used in [[Macedonian language|Macedonian]] to represent the [[voiced palatal plosive]] {{IPA|/\u025f/}}.\n\n\u0403 is most commonly romanized using the Latin letter G with [[Acute accent|acute]] {{angbr|\u01f5}}. When the [[Socialist Republic of Macedonia]] was part of [[SFR Yugoslavia]], the Macedonian '''\u0453''' was also transliterated as '''\u0111''' or '''dj'''.\n\nWords with this letter are often cognate with {{lang|bg|\u0436\u0434}} - ''zhd'' in [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] and  [[Dje]] (\u0402&nbsp;\u0452) in [[Serbian language|Serbian]]. For example, the Macedonian word for ''birth'' ({{lang|mk|\u0440\u0430\u0453\u0430\u045a\u0435}} is ''ra\u01f5anje'', which in Bulgarian is {{lang|bg|\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0435}} - ''razhdane'', and in Serbian {{lang|sr|\u0440\u0430\u0452\u0430\u045a\u0435}} - ''ra\u0111anje'').\n\n==Related letters and other similar characters==\n*\u0413 \u0433: [[Ge (Cyrillic)|Cyrillic letter Ge]]\n*\u0402 \u0452: [[Dje|Cyrillic letter Dje]]\n*\u040c \u045c: [[Kje|Cyrillic letter Kje]]\n\n{{anchor|Encodings}}\n\n==Computing codes==\n\n{{charmap\n|0403|name1=Cyrillic Capital Letter Gje\n|0453|name2=Cyrillic Small Letter Gje\n|map1=[[Code page 855]] |map1char1=83 |map1char2=82\n|map2=[[Windows-1251]] |map2char1=81 |map2char2=83\n|map3=[[ISO-8859-5]] |map3char1=A3 |map3char2=F3\n|map4=[[Macintosh Cyrillic encoding|Macintosh Cyrillic]] |map4char1=AE |map4char2=AF\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Wiktionary-inline|\u0403}}\n*{{Wiktionary-inline|\u0453}}\n\n\n{{Cyrillic-alphabet-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SrpskiAnonimac", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gje"}
{"title_page": "1703 in Japan", "text_new": "{{Year in Japan|-1000000}}\nEvents in the year '''-1000000in [[Japan]]'''.\n<!--\n==Incumbents==\n-->\n==Incumbents==\n*[[Monarchy of Japan|Monarch]]: [[Emperor Higashiyama|Higashiyama]]\n\n==Events==\n*January 30 - The famed [[Forty-seven Samurai]] avenge their leader, [[Asano Naganori]] out of loyalty by attacking and killing Kira Kozuke no Suke Yoshinaka, despite being ordered not to. (Traditional [[Japanese calendar|Japanese Date]]: Fourteenth Day of the Twelfth Month, 1702)\n<!--\n==Births==\n\n\n==Deaths==\n\n==See also==\n-->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Japan year nav}}\n{{Asia topic|1000000 BC in}}\n[[Category:1000000 BC in Japan| ]]\n[[Category:-1000000s in Japan]]\n[[Category:-1000000sby country|Japan]]\n[[Category:Years of the 1000000th century in Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Year in Japan|1703}}\nEvents in the year '''1703 in [[Japan]]'''.\n<!--\n==Incumbents==\n-->\n==Incumbents==\n*[[Monarchy of Japan|Monarch]]: [[Emperor Higashiyama|Higashiyama]]\n\n==Events==\n*January 30 - The famed [[Forty-seven Samurai]] avenge their leader, [[Asano Naganori]] out of loyalty by attacking and killing Kira Kozuke no Suke Yoshinaka, despite being ordered not to. (Traditional [[Japanese calendar|Japanese Date]]: Fourteenth Day of the Twelfth Month, 1702)\n<!--\n==Births==\n\n\n==Deaths==\n\n==See also==\n-->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Japan year nav}}\n{{Asia topic|1703 in}}\n[[Category:1703 in Japan| ]]\n[[Category:1700s in Japan]]\n[[Category:1703 by country|Japan]]\n[[Category:Years of the 18th century in Japan]]\n", "name_user": "2606:a000:1400:4551:786e:c1db:6f38:831e", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1703_in_Japan"}
{"title_page": "Derrycassan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Derrycassan townland.jpg|thumb|Derrycassan townland]]\n\n'''Derrycassan''' ({{Irish derived place name|Doire an C\u00e1sain meaning either the \"Path through the Oakwood\" or \"Cassan's Oakwood\" (Cassan being an early Irish form of the present name Cassidy}}) is a [[townland]] in the [[civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]] of [[Templeport]], [[County Cavan]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It lies in the Roman Catholic parish of [[Templeport]] and barony of [[Tullyhaw]]. The local pronunciation is ''Dorrahasson''.\n\n==Geography==\n\nDerrycassan is bounded on the north by [[Kilnavert]] and [[Corran, County Cavan|Corran]] townlands, on the  west by [[Camagh]],  [[Sruhagh]] and [[Gorteen, Templeport]] townlands, on the south by Derryniggin in [[County Leitrim]] and [[Burren (townland)|Burren]] townland and on the east by [[Coologe]] and [[Toberlyan]] townlands. Its chief geographical features are [[Coologe]] Lake, Derrycassan Lake and [[Camagh]] Lough. Derrycassan is traversed by a public road and several rural lanes. The townland covers 498 statute acres.<ref name=\"IreAtlas\"/>\n\n==History==\n\nThe earliest surviving mention of the townland name is ''Doire Cas\u00e1in'', which appears in an interesting list of the rents  due to the McGovern Chief, [[Maghnus 'Ruadh' M\u00e1g Samhradh\u00e1in]] about 1400 A.D.<ref>{{Citation |author= L. McKenna |title=The Book of Magauran |year=1947 |ref=BM}}</ref> It reads as follows:\n\n{{quote|This is the portion of Doire Cas\u00e1in- 18 kegs of butter and 8 cakes and half a beef at Christmas and a sheep in autumn and a sheep in summer and two kegs of butter in winter and 8 kegs of meal and as much again in autumn and a keg of butter for Mayday and a gallon of butter for his ploughman in summer.<ref>''Leabhar M\u00e9ig Shamradh\u00e1in, the MacGovern Poembook'' by\nNollaig \u00d3 Mura\u00edle, in \"Culture and society in early modern Breifne/Cavan\", Dublin 2009.</ref>}}\n\nFrom this list we see that in 1400 the main type of farming carried on in Derrycassan was milk and beef cattle together with sheep.\n\nA Roman poem from 91 A.D., the [[Thebaid (Latin poem)|Thebaid]] by Publius Papinius [[Statius]] was translated into Irish as ''Togail na Tebe''. This Irish version was transcribed in 1487 in Derrycassan by Diarmaid Bacach mac Parthalain (Dermot \"The Lame\" MacPartland), in the house of his father, Fineen mac Parthalain. The introduction to the translation translates as\n{{Quote|This book was written A.D. 1487, and in the same year died O'Reilly, to wit, Turlough, son of John; and in the same year were slain the sons of O'Rourke, to wit, Tiernan and Brian Roe, to wit, Tiernan was slain by the sons of MacDermot and by Muintir-Eolais in treachery, and Brian by a son of O'Rourke, to wit, by Owen, son of Felim, son of Donough, son of Tiernan; and in the same year was slain Tiernan Duv, son of Donough Blind-eye Tiernan by O'Donnell, to wit, by Hugh Roe O'Donnell; and in the same year was demolished the castle of O'Rourke, to wit, Felim, son of Donough by O'Donnell and by the sons of O'Rourke; and in the same year the fortress of Lough Oughter was taken possession of by the race of Donnell Ban O'Reilly. It was myself Dermot 'The Lame' MacPartland that transcribed this book, to wit, son of Fineen, son of Foirithe, son of Ferral, son of Farlane; and half of this book was written in the house of Fineen, to wit, in '''Derry Casan''', and the other part of it was written in the house of the descendants of Brian of Tullyhaw to wit the mansion house, to wit, of Felim, son of Teige Og, son of Teige Mor (son of Tadgh son of Filip son of Domhnall son of Maoleoin son of Brian son of Macraith son of the McGovern chief [[Donnchadh \u2018Cime\u2019 M\u00e1g Samhradh\u00e1in]] d.1269); and it was finished in Inishowen upon Thursday during the feast of St Catherine. (Diarmaid Bacach mac Parthalain doscribh in leabar-sa .i. mac Fingin mic Foirithe mic Fergail mic Partalain & a tigh Fingin doscribad leth in lebair-sa .i. a Doire Casain & a tigh mic Briain Tellaigh-Echach dos-cribad in cuid ele de .i. a tigh arosa .i. Feidhlimid mac Taidhg oig mic Taidhg moir & ar iniss Eocinain docrichnuighedh e i nDardain re feil Catrina) And G is the Dominical Letter in that year and S the Golden Number. And the hospitality of the son of Thomas the son of Fergus son of that Thomas lord of Tullyhaw during the time when this book was written. And at the same period there were two bishops in the bishopric of Kilmore, to wit, Cormac, son of the bishop Magauran, and Thomas son of Andrew MacBrady, each one of them alleging that he himself is bishop there; and Felim, son of Donough, son of Tiernan is O'Rourke during the period of those bishops, and John son of Turlough son of John is O'Reilly at that time. And in the same year was slain Ua Mael-Shechlain, to wit, Laighnech Ua Mael-Shechlain, by Conn son of Art ua MaelShechlain. And may the blessing of God rest on the soul of him that wrote this book. And there was war between Magauran and O'Reilly, to wit, John O'Reilly, in that same year; and another war between the descendants of Teige O'Rourke, etc.<ref>Togail na Tebe: The Thebaid of Statius:, ed. George Calder (Cambridge: University Press 1922).</ref>}}\n\nDiarmaid Bacach mac Parthalain also wrote or transcribed the following, some in Tullyhaw, probably in Derrycassan.<ref>Diarmuid O Laoghaire, \"Beathai naomh iasachta sa Ghaeilge\" (unpublished Ph.D. thesis, University. College Dublin, 1967), p.xxx.</ref> (1) ''Tochmarc Becfhola or The Wooing of Becfola''.<ref>Bhreathnach, M\u00e1ire. ''A new edition of Tochmarc Becfhola'' in \u00c9riu 35 (1984) Pages 59\u201391.</ref> (2) ''Irish translations of romantic tales, lives of saints and other religious texts''.<ref>[http://sources.nli.ie/Record/MS_UR_047168]</ref> (3) ''D\u00e1n do Chormac M\u00e1g Shamhradh\u00e1in Easpag Ardachaidh''.<ref>''D\u00e1n do Chormac M\u00e1g Shamhradh\u00e1in Easpag Ardachaidh'' by Gear\u00f3id Mac Niocaill in Seanchas Ardmhacha, vol. 4, no. 1 (1960-61), pp. 141-146.</ref>\n\nHis brother Conall Ballach Mac Parthal\u00e1in (Conall \"The Freckled\" MacPartland) was also a scribe. He produced part of the manuscript Rawlinson B 513 [[Bodleian Library]], Oxford, England.<ref>\u00d3 Con Cheanainn, Tom\u00e1s: ''Scr\u00edobha\u00ed \u2018Leabhar Mhuintir Laidhe\u2019 agus \u2018Rosa Anglica\u2019'', in \u00c9igse 37 (2010), pp. 112\u2013118.</ref>\n\nThe 1609 Baronial Map depicts the townland as ''Dirricasan''.<ref>National Archives Dublin: [http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documents/mpf1-58.pdf]</ref> <ref>[http://www.templeport.ie/pages/1609-TP-Baronial-Map.html]</ref> The 1652 Commonwealth Survey spells the name as ''Derrecassan''. The 1665 Down Survey map depicts it as ''Derrycashan''.<ref>Trinity College Dublin: [http://downsurvey.tcd.ie/down-survey-maps.php#bm=Tullaghhagh&c=Cavan&indexOfObjectValue=-1&indexOfObjectValueSubstring=-1 The Down Survey of Ireland.]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Plantation of Ulster]] by grant dated 29 April 1611, along with other lands, King James I granted the two polls of ''Dirricassan'' to the McGovern Chief, [[Feidhlimidh M\u00e1g Samhradh\u00e1in]]<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XD5JAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA211&dq=boely+Killmuriertagh&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjBzuSOzbjfAhWjQxUIHZeBAogQ6AEINTAC#v=onepage&q=boely%20Killmuriertagh&f=false]</ref>, but it is probable that the lands had been in the possession of the McGovern clan for several hundred years before this and it was just a [[Surrender and regrant]] confirming the existing title to the McGoverns.\n\nAn Inquisition of King [[Charles I of England]] held in Cavan town on 4 October 1626 stated that the aforesaid Phelim Magawrane died on 20 January 1622 and his lands including two polls of Derricassan went to his son, the McGovern chief [[Brian Magauran]] who was aged 30 (born 1592) and married.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WUepqE-K4PAC&pg=PR113&lpg=PR113&dq=dromcorck&source=bl&ots=q1nwNi30To&sig=juFN_wB-OVUyQQWNLXCgd5Y2MMk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjQ9fmXzrjfAhXlsnEKHTVBAhoQ6AEwBnoECAQQAQ#v=onepage&q=dromcorck&f=false]</ref>\n\nThe McGovern lands in Derrycassan were confiscated in the Cromwellian [[Act for the Settlement of Ireland 1652]] and were distributed as follows-\n\nThe 1652 Commonwealth Survey lists the proprietor as ''John King & others''. \n\nIn the Hearth Money Rolls compiled on 29 September 1663<ref>''The Hearth Money Rolls for the Baronies of Tullyhunco and Tullyhaw, County Cavan'', edited by Rev. Francis J. McKiernan, in Breifne Journal. Vol. I, No. 3 (1960), pp. 247-263</ref> there were three Hearth Tax payers in  ''Dirilussno- James Meeke, Robert Turner and Shane O'Killyn''.\n\nA grant dated 1667 from King Charles II to James Thornton included 191  acres and two roods in ''Derrycassan''.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/op1244157-1001#page/n121/mode/2up/search/evallaghmore]</ref> \n\nA grant dated 7 July 1669 from King Charles II to John, Lord Viscount Massareene included five acres in ''Derrychashen''.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/op1244157-1001#page/n177/mode/2up/search/Aughwoonagh]</ref>\n\nA deed dated 8 June 1730 by ''John Johnston of Currin'' refers to lands in ''Derryhassan''.<ref>[https://irishdeedsindex.net/mem.php?memorial=43704]</ref>\n\nThe 1790 Cavan Carvaghs list spells the townland name as ''Derrycassar''.<ref>[http://www.cavanlibrary.ie/file/Local-Studies/Library-Scanned-Docs/The-Carvaghs-A-List-Of-The-Several-Baronies-And-Parishes-in-the-County-Of-Cavan.pdf]</ref>\n\nIn the 1825 Registry of Freeholders for County Cavan there were six freeholders registered in Derrycassan- Thomas Breden, Patrick Gannon, Francis Logan, Owen M'Dermott, Edward Maher and Myles Rorke. They were all [[Forty-shilling freeholders]] holding a lease for lives from their landlord. William Blashford of [[Lissanover]].[http://www.cavanlibrary.ie/file/Local-Studies/Library-Scanned-Docs/Registry-of-Freeholders-in-the-County-of-Cavan.pdf]\n\nThe Tithe Applotment Books for 1827 list one hundred and forty five tithepayers in the townland.<ref>[http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Derrycassan%20Upper&search=Search]  [http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Derrycassan%20Lower&search=Search] [http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?surname=&firstname=&county=Cavan&townland=Derrynenantha+Lower&parish=Templeport&search=Search&sort=&pageSize=&pager.offset=10] ''Tithe Applotment Books 1827''</ref>\n\nIn 1833 two people in Derrycassan were registered as a keeper of weapons- Thomas Bredin and William Lauder.<ref>[http://www.bawnboy.com/local-genealogy/arms-keepers-templeport-1833.html]</ref>\n\nThe Derrycassan Valuation Office Field books are available for November 1839.<ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00365.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00366.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00367.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00368.pdf]</ref>\n\nIn 1841 the population of the townland was 253, being 132 males and 121 females. There were forty-eight houses in the townland, all of which were inhabited.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=96RbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA95&dq=leitra+cavan+-lyrics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIiq76x9rZAhXLDewKHexcCA0Q6AEIPjAE#v=onepage&q=leitra%20&f=false]</ref>\n\nIn 1851 the population of the townland was 191, being 105 males and 86 females, the reduction being due to the Great Famine (Ireland). There were forty-three in the townland, four of which were uninhabited.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=96RbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA95&dq=leitra+cavan+-lyrics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIiq76x9rZAhXLDewKHexcCA0Q6AEIPjAE#v=onepage&q=leitra%20&f=false]</ref>\n\n[[Griffith's Valuation]] of 1857 lists sixty eight landholders in the townland.<ref>[http://www.askaboutireland.ie/griffith-valuation/index.xml?action=doNameSearch&PlaceID=190676&county=Cavan&barony=Tullyhaw&parish=Templeport&townland=%3Cb%3EDerrycassan%3C/b%3E] - Derrycassan</ref>\n\nIn 1861 the population of the townland was 151, being 75 males and 76 females. There were thirty-six houses in the townland and all were inhabited.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951p00771975o;view=1up;seq=107;size=175]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Census of Ireland, 1901|1901 census of Ireland]], there are twenty nine families listed in the townland.<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1901/Cavan/Lisanover/Derrycasson/ Census of Ireland 1901]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Census of Ireland, 1911|1911 census of Ireland]], there are twenty two families listed in the townland.<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1911/Cavan/Lissanover/Derrycassan/ Census of Ireland 1911]</ref>\n\n==Antiquities==\n\nThe chief structures of historical interest in the townland are: \n# An earthen ringfort.<ref>Site number 505 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O'Donovan, 1995, where it is described as-\n''Marked 'Fort' on OS 1836 and 1876 eds. A slightly raised, formerly oval-shaped area enclosed by a substantial bank and a wide, shallow fosse from NNW-E-SE. Elsewhere, site has been largely levelled. Original entrance not recognisable. Internal area slopes quite steeply from NE-SW''.</ref> \n# An earthen ringfort.<ref>Site number 506 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O'Donovan, 1995, where it is described as-\n''Situated on SSW slope of a high drumlin ridge overlooking Derrycassan Lough c. 40m to S. Raised oval area (int. dims. 38.3m E-W; c. 28m N-S) enclosed by an earthen bank which is substantial from W-N-E and more poorly defined elsewhere, and a wide, deep fosse. At E the perimeter has been defaced as a result of the erection of a field boundary. An earlier report (OPW 1969) noted that the original entrance was at E''.</ref> \n# A crann\u00f3g in Derrycassan lake. An ancient stone axe was found there in 1935 and is now in the National Museum of Ireland.<ref>Site number 1536 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O'Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- ''Situated in a reed-and-scrub-covered area on what is presently the N shore of a channel linking Derrycassan and Coologe Loughs. During the cleaning of a drain in 1992, a number of vertical timbers were revealed some of which were pointed, while others had possible mortices. Nearby there were horizontal timbers and deposits of stone and peat. It is believed (OPW 1992) that the remains represent the edge of a circular crann\u00f3g (diam. 25m-30m)''.</ref><ref>[https://www.academia.edu/3670344/The_Plain_of_Blood_A_Study_of_the_Ritual_Landscape_of_Magh_Slecht_Co._Cavan]</ref>\n# A crann\u00f3g in Derrycassan lake.<ref>Site number 1537 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O'Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- ''Not marked on OS 1836 or 1876 eds. Small oval island (dims. c. 30m WNW-ESE; c.20m NNE-SSW) in Ballymaguaran Lough, c. 200m from the shoreline''.</ref> <ref>[https://www.academia.edu/3670344/The_Plain_of_Blood_A_Study_of_the_Ritual_Landscape_of_Magh_Slecht_Co._Cavan]</ref>\n# A medieval [[Bullaun]] Stone is located in the townland, which local tradition claims is a cure for warts.<ref>Site number 1639 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- ''Irregularly shaped earthfast stone (max. dims. 0.85m x 0.75m) with a circular bullaun (diam. 0.23m; D 0.18m) in its upper surface at one end, accompanied by three shallow depressions (dims. 0.05-0.06m) roughly arranged in an arc. Tradition that it was a cure for warts (local information)''.</ref> <ref>[http://www.megalithomania.com/show/site/1559]</ref> \n# In 1863 a small, very perfect, copper battle-axe, 61 inches long, and 3 inches wide, with four rivets and an iron weapon-tool, adze-shaped on one side, and hatchet on the other, 9 inches long were found in Derrycassan.<ref>''Proceedings of the Royal Irish Academy'' 1864, Vol. 8, p.328</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"IreAtlas\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ |title=IreAtlas |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ The IreAtlas Townland Data Base]\n*[http://www.bawnboy.com/History-Heritage-Folklore/pages/derrycassan-diary.html Diary of a Derrycassan farming family in the 1940s]\n# Salvador Ryan, \u2018Wily women of God\u2019 in \"Cavan\u2019s late medieval and early modern devotional collections\", in Brendan Scott (ed.), Culture and society in early modern Breifne/Cavan (Dublin: Four Courts Press, 2009) [https://www.academia.edu/12606832/_Wily_women_of_God_in_Cavan_s_late_medieval_and_early_modern_devotional_collections_in_Brendan_Scott_ed._Culture_and_society_in_early_modern_Breifne_Cavan_Dublin_Four_Courts_Press_2009]\n\n{{County Cavan}}\n\n[[Category:Townlands of County Cavan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Derrycassan townland.jpg|thumb|Derrycassan townland]]\n\n'''Derrycassan''' ({{Irish derived place name|Doire an C\u00e1sain meaning either the \"Path through the Oakwood\" or \"Cassan's Oakwood\" (Cassan being an early Irish form of the present name Cassidy}}) is a [[townland]] in the [[civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]] of [[Templeport]], [[County Cavan]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It lies in the Roman Catholic parish of [[Templeport]] and barony of [[Tullyhaw]]. The local pronunciation is ''Dorrahasson''.\n\n==Geography==\n\nDerrycassan is bounded on the north by [[Kilnavert]] and [[Corran, County Cavan|Corran]] townlands, on the  west by [[Camagh]],  [[Sruhagh]] and [[Gorteen, Templeport]] townlands, on the south by Derryniggin in [[County Leitrim]] and [[Burren (townland)|Burren]] townland and on the east by [[Coologe]] and [[Toberlyan]] townlands. Its chief geographical features are [[Coologe]] Lake, Derrycassan Lake and [[Camagh]] Lough. Derrycassan is traversed by a public road and several rural lanes. The townland covers 498 statute acres.<ref name=\"IreAtlas\"/>\n\n==History==\n\nThe earliest surviving mention of the townland name is ''Doire Cas\u00e1in'', which appears in an interesting list of the rents  due to the McGovern Chief, [[Maghnus 'Ruadh' M\u00e1g Samhradh\u00e1in]] about 1400 A.D.<ref>{{Citation |author= L. McKenna |title=The Book of Magauran |year=1947 |ref=BM}}</ref> It reads as follows:\n\n{{quote|This is the portion of Doire Cas\u00e1in- 18 kegs of butter and 8 cakes and half a beef at Christmas and a sheep in autumn and a sheep in summer and two kegs of butter in winter and 8 kegs of meal and as much again in autumn and a keg of butter for Mayday and a gallon of butter for his ploughman in summer.<ref>''Leabhar M\u00e9ig Shamradh\u00e1in, the MacGovern Poembook'' by\nNollaig \u00d3 Mura\u00edle, in \"Culture and society in early modern Breifne/Cavan\", Dublin 2009.</ref>}}\n\nFrom this list we see that in 1400 the main type of farming carried on in Derrycassan was milk and beef cattle together with sheep.\n\nA Roman poem from 91 A.D., the [[Thebaid (Latin poem)|Thebaid]] by Publius Papinius [[Statius]] was translated into Irish as ''Togail na Tebe''. This Irish version was transcribed in 1487 in Derrycassan by Diarmaid Bacach mac Parthalain (Dermot \"The Lame\" MacPartland), in the house of his father, Fineen mac Parthalain. The introduction to the translation translates as\n{{Quote|This book was written A.D. 1487, and in the same year died O'Reilly, to wit, Turlough, son of John; and in the same year were slain the sons of O'Rourke, to wit, Tiernan and Brian Roe, to wit, Tiernan was slain by the sons of MacDermot and by Muintir-Eolais in treachery, and Brian by a son of O'Rourke, to wit, by Owen, son of Felim, son of Donough, son of Tiernan; and in the same year was slain Tiernan Duv, son of Donough Blind-eye Tiernan by O'Donnell, to wit, by Hugh Roe O'Donnell; and in the same year was demolished the castle of O'Rourke, to wit, Felim, son of Donough by O'Donnell and by the sons of O'Rourke; and in the same year the fortress of Lough Oughter was taken possession of by the race of Donnell Ban O'Reilly. It was myself Dermot 'The Lame' MacPartland that transcribed this book, to wit, son of Fineen, son of Foirithe, son of Ferral, son of Farlane; and half of this book was written in the house of Fineen, to wit, in '''Derry Casan''', and the other part of it was written in the house of the descendants of Brian of Tullyhaw to wit the mansion house, to wit, of Felim, son of Teige Og, son of Teige Mor (son of Tadgh son of Filip son of Domhnall son of Maoleoin son of Brian son of Macraith son of the McGovern chief [[Donnchadh \u2018Cime\u2019 M\u00e1g Samhradh\u00e1in]] d.1269); and it was finished on the Island of Inishannon upon Thursday during the feast of St Catherine. (Diarmaid Bacach mac Parthalain doscribh in leabar-sa .i. mac Fingin mic Foirithe mic Fergail mic Partalain & a tigh Fingin doscribad leth in lebair-sa .i. a Doire Casain & a tigh mic Briain Tellaigh-Echach dos-cribad in cuid ele de .i. a tigh arosa .i. Feidhlimid mac Taidhg oig mic Taidhg moir & ar iniss Eocinain docrichnuighedh e i nDardain re feil Catrina) And G is the Dominical Letter in that year and S the Golden Number. And the hospitality of the son of Thomas the son of Fergus son of that Thomas lord of Tullyhaw during the time when this book was written. And at the same period there were two bishops in the bishopric of Kilmore, to wit, Cormac, son of the bishop Magauran, and Thomas son of Andrew MacBrady, each one of them alleging that he himself is bishop there; and Felim, son of Donough, son of Tiernan is O'Rourke during the period of those bishops, and John son of Turlough son of John is O'Reilly at that time. And in the same year was slain Ua Mael-Shechlain, to wit, Laighnech Ua Mael-Shechlain, by Conn son of Art ua MaelShechlain. And may the blessing of God rest on the soul of him that wrote this book. And there was war between Magauran and O'Reilly, to wit, John O'Reilly, in that same year; and another war between the descendants of Teige O'Rourke, etc.<ref>Togail na Tebe: The Thebaid of Statius:, ed. George Calder (Cambridge: University Press 1922).</ref>}}\n\nDiarmaid Bacach mac Parthalain also wrote or transcribed the following, some in Tullyhaw, probably in Derrycassan.<ref>Diarmuid O Laoghaire, \"Beathai naomh iasachta sa Ghaeilge\" (unpublished Ph.D. thesis, University. College Dublin, 1967), p.xxx.</ref> (1) ''Tochmarc Becfhola or The Wooing of Becfola''.<ref>Bhreathnach, M\u00e1ire. ''A new edition of Tochmarc Becfhola'' in \u00c9riu 35 (1984) Pages 59\u201391.</ref> (2) ''Irish translations of romantic tales, lives of saints and other religious texts''.<ref>[http://sources.nli.ie/Record/MS_UR_047168]</ref> (3) ''D\u00e1n do Chormac M\u00e1g Shamhradh\u00e1in Easpag Ardachaidh''.<ref>''D\u00e1n do Chormac M\u00e1g Shamhradh\u00e1in Easpag Ardachaidh'' by Gear\u00f3id Mac Niocaill in Seanchas Ardmhacha, vol. 4, no. 1 (1960-61), pp. 141-146.</ref>\n\nHis brother Conall Ballach Mac Parthal\u00e1in (Conall \"The Freckled\" MacPartland) was also a scribe. He produced part of the manuscript Rawlinson B 513 [[Bodleian Library]], Oxford, England.<ref>\u00d3 Con Cheanainn, Tom\u00e1s: ''Scr\u00edobha\u00ed \u2018Leabhar Mhuintir Laidhe\u2019 agus \u2018Rosa Anglica\u2019'', in \u00c9igse 37 (2010), pp. 112\u2013118.</ref>\n\nThe 1609 Baronial Map depicts the townland as ''Dirricasan''.<ref>National Archives Dublin: [http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documents/mpf1-58.pdf]</ref> <ref>[http://www.templeport.ie/pages/1609-TP-Baronial-Map.html]</ref> The 1652 Commonwealth Survey spells the name as ''Derrecassan''. The 1665 Down Survey map depicts it as ''Derrycashan''.<ref>Trinity College Dublin: [http://downsurvey.tcd.ie/down-survey-maps.php#bm=Tullaghhagh&c=Cavan&indexOfObjectValue=-1&indexOfObjectValueSubstring=-1 The Down Survey of Ireland.]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Plantation of Ulster]] by grant dated 29 April 1611, along with other lands, King James I granted the two polls of ''Dirricassan'' to the McGovern Chief, [[Feidhlimidh M\u00e1g Samhradh\u00e1in]]<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=XD5JAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA211&dq=boely+Killmuriertagh&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjBzuSOzbjfAhWjQxUIHZeBAogQ6AEINTAC#v=onepage&q=boely%20Killmuriertagh&f=false]</ref>, but it is probable that the lands had been in the possession of the McGovern clan for several hundred years before this and it was just a [[Surrender and regrant]] confirming the existing title to the McGoverns.\n\nAn Inquisition of King [[Charles I of England]] held in Cavan town on 4 October 1626 stated that the aforesaid Phelim Magawrane died on 20 January 1622 and his lands including two polls of Derricassan went to his son, the McGovern chief [[Brian Magauran]] who was aged 30 (born 1592) and married.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WUepqE-K4PAC&pg=PR113&lpg=PR113&dq=dromcorck&source=bl&ots=q1nwNi30To&sig=juFN_wB-OVUyQQWNLXCgd5Y2MMk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjQ9fmXzrjfAhXlsnEKHTVBAhoQ6AEwBnoECAQQAQ#v=onepage&q=dromcorck&f=false]</ref>\n\nThe McGovern lands in Derrycassan were confiscated in the Cromwellian [[Act for the Settlement of Ireland 1652]] and were distributed as follows-\n\nThe 1652 Commonwealth Survey lists the proprietor as ''John King & others''. \n\nIn the Hearth Money Rolls compiled on 29 September 1663<ref>''The Hearth Money Rolls for the Baronies of Tullyhunco and Tullyhaw, County Cavan'', edited by Rev. Francis J. McKiernan, in Breifne Journal. Vol. I, No. 3 (1960), pp. 247-263</ref> there were three Hearth Tax payers in  ''Dirilussno- James Meeke, Robert Turner and Shane O'Killyn''.\n\nA grant dated 1667 from King Charles II to James Thornton included 191  acres and two roods in ''Derrycassan''.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/op1244157-1001#page/n121/mode/2up/search/evallaghmore]</ref> \n\nA grant dated 7 July 1669 from King Charles II to John, Lord Viscount Massareene included five acres in ''Derrychashen''.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/op1244157-1001#page/n177/mode/2up/search/Aughwoonagh]</ref>\n\nA deed dated 8 June 1730 by ''John Johnston of Currin'' refers to lands in ''Derryhassan''.<ref>[https://irishdeedsindex.net/mem.php?memorial=43704]</ref>\n\nThe 1790 Cavan Carvaghs list spells the townland name as ''Derrycassar''.<ref>[http://www.cavanlibrary.ie/file/Local-Studies/Library-Scanned-Docs/The-Carvaghs-A-List-Of-The-Several-Baronies-And-Parishes-in-the-County-Of-Cavan.pdf]</ref>\n\nIn the 1825 Registry of Freeholders for County Cavan there were six freeholders registered in Derrycassan- Thomas Breden, Patrick Gannon, Francis Logan, Owen M'Dermott, Edward Maher and Myles Rorke. They were all [[Forty-shilling freeholders]] holding a lease for lives from their landlord. William Blashford of [[Lissanover]].[http://www.cavanlibrary.ie/file/Local-Studies/Library-Scanned-Docs/Registry-of-Freeholders-in-the-County-of-Cavan.pdf]\n\nThe Tithe Applotment Books for 1827 list one hundred and forty five tithepayers in the townland.<ref>[http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Derrycassan%20Upper&search=Search]  [http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Derrycassan%20Lower&search=Search] [http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?surname=&firstname=&county=Cavan&townland=Derrynenantha+Lower&parish=Templeport&search=Search&sort=&pageSize=&pager.offset=10] ''Tithe Applotment Books 1827''</ref>\n\nIn 1833 two people in Derrycassan were registered as a keeper of weapons- Thomas Bredin and William Lauder.<ref>[http://www.bawnboy.com/local-genealogy/arms-keepers-templeport-1833.html]</ref>\n\nThe Derrycassan Valuation Office Field books are available for November 1839.<ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00365.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00366.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00367.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00368.pdf]</ref>\n\nIn 1841 the population of the townland was 253, being 132 males and 121 females. There were forty-eight houses in the townland, all of which were inhabited.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=96RbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA95&dq=leitra+cavan+-lyrics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIiq76x9rZAhXLDewKHexcCA0Q6AEIPjAE#v=onepage&q=leitra%20&f=false]</ref>\n\nIn 1851 the population of the townland was 191, being 105 males and 86 females, the reduction being due to the Great Famine (Ireland). There were forty-three in the townland, four of which were uninhabited.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=96RbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA95&dq=leitra+cavan+-lyrics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIiq76x9rZAhXLDewKHexcCA0Q6AEIPjAE#v=onepage&q=leitra%20&f=false]</ref>\n\n[[Griffith's Valuation]] of 1857 lists sixty eight landholders in the townland.<ref>[http://www.askaboutireland.ie/griffith-valuation/index.xml?action=doNameSearch&PlaceID=190676&county=Cavan&barony=Tullyhaw&parish=Templeport&townland=%3Cb%3EDerrycassan%3C/b%3E] - Derrycassan</ref>\n\nIn 1861 the population of the townland was 151, being 75 males and 76 females. There were thirty-six houses in the townland and all were inhabited.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951p00771975o;view=1up;seq=107;size=175]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Census of Ireland, 1901|1901 census of Ireland]], there are twenty nine families listed in the townland.<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1901/Cavan/Lisanover/Derrycasson/ Census of Ireland 1901]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Census of Ireland, 1911|1911 census of Ireland]], there are twenty two families listed in the townland.<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1911/Cavan/Lissanover/Derrycassan/ Census of Ireland 1911]</ref>\n\n==Antiquities==\n\nThe chief structures of historical interest in the townland are: \n# An earthen ringfort.<ref>Site number 505 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O'Donovan, 1995, where it is described as-\n''Marked 'Fort' on OS 1836 and 1876 eds. A slightly raised, formerly oval-shaped area enclosed by a substantial bank and a wide, shallow fosse from NNW-E-SE. Elsewhere, site has been largely levelled. Original entrance not recognisable. Internal area slopes quite steeply from NE-SW''.</ref> \n# An earthen ringfort.<ref>Site number 506 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O'Donovan, 1995, where it is described as-\n''Situated on SSW slope of a high drumlin ridge overlooking Derrycassan Lough c. 40m to S. Raised oval area (int. dims. 38.3m E-W; c. 28m N-S) enclosed by an earthen bank which is substantial from W-N-E and more poorly defined elsewhere, and a wide, deep fosse. At E the perimeter has been defaced as a result of the erection of a field boundary. An earlier report (OPW 1969) noted that the original entrance was at E''.</ref> \n# A crann\u00f3g in Derrycassan lake. An ancient stone axe was found there in 1935 and is now in the National Museum of Ireland.<ref>Site number 1536 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O'Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- ''Situated in a reed-and-scrub-covered area on what is presently the N shore of a channel linking Derrycassan and Coologe Loughs. During the cleaning of a drain in 1992, a number of vertical timbers were revealed some of which were pointed, while others had possible mortices. Nearby there were horizontal timbers and deposits of stone and peat. It is believed (OPW 1992) that the remains represent the edge of a circular crann\u00f3g (diam. 25m-30m)''.</ref><ref>[https://www.academia.edu/3670344/The_Plain_of_Blood_A_Study_of_the_Ritual_Landscape_of_Magh_Slecht_Co._Cavan]</ref>\n# A crann\u00f3g in Derrycassan lake.<ref>Site number 1537 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O'Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- ''Not marked on OS 1836 or 1876 eds. Small oval island (dims. c. 30m WNW-ESE; c.20m NNE-SSW) in Ballymaguaran Lough, c. 200m from the shoreline''.</ref> <ref>[https://www.academia.edu/3670344/The_Plain_of_Blood_A_Study_of_the_Ritual_Landscape_of_Magh_Slecht_Co._Cavan]</ref>\n# A medieval [[Bullaun]] Stone is located in the townland, which local tradition claims is a cure for warts.<ref>Site number 1639 in ''Archaeological Inventory of County Cavan'', Patrick O\u2019Donovan, 1995, where it is described as- ''Irregularly shaped earthfast stone (max. dims. 0.85m x 0.75m) with a circular bullaun (diam. 0.23m; D 0.18m) in its upper surface at one end, accompanied by three shallow depressions (dims. 0.05-0.06m) roughly arranged in an arc. Tradition that it was a cure for warts (local information)''.</ref> <ref>[http://www.megalithomania.com/show/site/1559]</ref> \n# In 1863 a small, very perfect, copper battle-axe, 61 inches long, and 3 inches wide, with four rivets and an iron weapon-tool, adze-shaped on one side, and hatchet on the other, 9 inches long were found in Derrycassan.<ref>''Proceedings of the Royal Irish Academy'' 1864, Vol. 8, p.328</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"IreAtlas\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ |title=IreAtlas |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ The IreAtlas Townland Data Base]\n*[http://www.bawnboy.com/History-Heritage-Folklore/pages/derrycassan-diary.html Diary of a Derrycassan farming family in the 1940s]\n# Salvador Ryan, \u2018Wily women of God\u2019 in \"Cavan\u2019s late medieval and early modern devotional collections\", in Brendan Scott (ed.), Culture and society in early modern Breifne/Cavan (Dublin: Four Courts Press, 2009) [https://www.academia.edu/12606832/_Wily_women_of_God_in_Cavan_s_late_medieval_and_early_modern_devotional_collections_in_Brendan_Scott_ed._Culture_and_society_in_early_modern_Breifne_Cavan_Dublin_Four_Courts_Press_2009]\n\n{{County Cavan}}\n\n[[Category:Townlands of County Cavan]]\n", "name_user": "Cormac1cormac1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derrycassan"}
