{"title_page": "Satellite flare", "text_new": "<!-- lead images -->\n{| class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 300px\" \n|-\n|\n{| style=\"background: white; white-space: nowrap;\" cellpadding=0 cellspacing=2\n|-\n| colspan=2 | [[File:Flare Simulation.gif|302px|]]\n|-\n|[[File:Iridium flare 2008 08 11.jpg|x100px|]]&thinsp;[[File:Comet holmes and iridium flare.jpg|x100px|]];[[file:Iridium flare in Cassiopeia.webm|x100px|]]\n|}\n|-\n|\n* Top: a simulated animation of a typical Iridium flare\n* Middle: Both images show a flare of an [[Iridium satellite constellation|Iridium satellite]]. Comet [[17P/Holmes|Holmes]] can be seen in the right image, slightly above the tree branch.\n*Bottom: Video of a flare\n|}\n\n'''Satellite flare''', also known as '''satellite glint''', is a [[Artificial satellite|satellite]] [[pass (spaceflight)|pass]] [[human vision|visible]] to the [[naked eye]] as a brief, bright \"[[flare]]\". It is caused by the reflection toward the Earth below of sunlight incident on satellite surfaces such as [[Photovoltaic module|solar panels]] and [[Antenna (radio)|antennas]] (e.g., [[Synthetic aperture radar|SAR]]).\n\nThe first generation of the [[Iridium satellite constellation|Iridium constellation]] with 66 active telecommunication satellites in [[low Earth orbit]] were known to cause '''Iridium flares''', the brightest flares of all [[Geocentric orbit|orbiting]] satellites. Throughout 2017 and 2018 they are being replaced with a new generation that does not produce flares, with the first generation expected to be completely phased out by late 2018.\n\n== Controlled satellites ==\n[[File:Iridium animation.gif|thumb|Flaring from reflection of the Sun]]\nTime and place of the satellite's flare can be predicted only when the satellite is controlled, and its orientation in space is known. In this case it is possible to predict the exact time of the flare, its place in the sky, the brightness and duration.\n\n=== Iridium flares ===\n[[File:Iridium 6 & 51.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Double flare - Iridium 6 and its replacement, #51, both flare in a 21-second exposure.]]\nIf a first-generation Iridium satellite is still controlled, its flares can be predicted.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Peat|first=Chris|date=2018-05-15|location=[[Munich]]|website=Heavens-Above|url=https://www.heavens-above.com/IridiumDemise.aspx|title=The end of Iridium flares?|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref> The [[Iridium satellite constellation|Iridium communication satellites]] have three polished door-sized antennas, 120\u00b0 apart and at 40\u00b0 angles with the main bus. The forward antenna faces the direction the satellite is traveling. Occasionally, an antenna reflects sunlight directly down at Earth, creating a predictable and quickly moving illuminated spot on the surface below of about {{convert|10|km|abbr=on}} diameter. To an observer this looks like a bright flash, or flare in the sky, with a duration of a few seconds.\n\nRanging up to \u22129.5 [[apparent magnitude|magnitude]], some of the flares are so bright that they can be seen in the daytime. This flashing has caused some annoyance to [[Astronomer#Modern astronomers|astronomers]], as the flares occasionally disturb observations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apollosat.com/iridium-flare-satellite-tracker/|title=Iridium Flare Satellite Tracker|website=Apollo Satellite Communications|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref>\n\nAs the Iridium constellation consists of 66 working satellites, Iridium flares are visible quite often (2\u20134 times per night). Flares of brightness \u22125 magnitude occur 3\u20134 times per week; \u22128 magnitude may be visible 3\u20135 times per month for stationary observers.\n\nFlares may also occur from solar panels, but they are not as bright (up to \u22123.5 magnitude). Such flares last about twice as long as those from the main mission antennas (MMA), because the so-called \"mirror angle\" for the solar panels is twice that for the MMAs. There are also rare cases of flares from MMAs and solar panels, or two MMAs (front and either right or left) of one satellite in a single [[pass (spaceflight)|pass]].\n\nThe flares can be bright enough to be seen at night in big cities where light pollution usually prevents most stellar observation. When not flaring, the satellites are often visible crossing the night sky at a typical magnitude of 6, similar to a dim star.\n\nThroughout 2017 and 2018, a new generation of Iridium satellites is being deployed which does not exhibit the characteristic flares. As the first generation have been replaced and retired, flares have become less frequent. The last of the first-generation satellites are expected to be deorbited in late 2018, ending predictable Iridium flares.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.skyatnightmagazine.com/news/iridium-flares-cease-end-2018|title=Iridium flares to cease by end of 2018|last=Carter |first=Jamie |date=2017-11-14 |website=BBC Sky at Night Magazine|language=en |access-date=2018-05-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Non-Iridium flares ===\n{{noref section|date=June 2018}}\n[[File:COSMO Skymed flare.PNG|thumb|180px|A [[COSMO-SkyMed]] flare]] \n[[File:MetOp-A satellite flare May 26 2019.jpg|thumb|180px|A MetOp-A flare]]\n\nThere are many controlled satellites in addition to Iridium satellites, which can also flare, but most flares of these satellites do not exceed magnitude \u22122, and are therefore often overlooked.\n\n[[MetOp|MetOp-A, B, and C]], however, can produce predictable flares up to \u22125 magnitude. Four [[COSMO-SkyMed]] satellites can produce flares up to \u22124 magnitude, and lasting much longer than the Iridium flares.\n\nThe [[International Space Station]] (ISS) is known to cause bright [[ISS flare]]s.<ref>[https://www.skyandtelescope.com/observing/watch-international-space-station/]</ref><ref>[https://www.universetoday.com/142187/the-international-space-station-rides-high-through-the-may-sky/]</ref><ref>[https://www.space.com/5610-spot-space-station.html]</ref><ref>[https://spotthestation.nasa.gov/]</ref>\n\nPlanned low-orbit satellite constellations such as [[Starlink]] are a concern for the astronomical community because of [[light pollution]].<ref>{{cite web|title=After SpaceX Starlink Launch, a Fear of Satellites That Outnumber All Visible Stars |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/01/science/starlink-spacex-astronomers.html|website=The New York Times|accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The unexpected brightness of new satellites could ruin the night sky|website=The Economist|url=https://www.economist.com/science-and-technology/2019/05/30/the-unexpected-brightness-of-new-satellites-could-ruin-the-night-sky|accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=SpaceX's Starlink Could Change The Night Sky Forever, And Astronomers Are Not Happy|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jonathanocallaghan/2019/05/27/spacexs-starlink-could-change-the-night-sky-forever-and-astronomers-are-not-happy/|website=Forbes|accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Uncontrolled satellites ==\n\nWhen the satellite's orientation goes out of control, it becomes possible to predict only a trajectory of its pass, at any point of which it can flare up. These satellites are also described as \"tumbling\". This category includes a lot of rotating rocket bodies, some failed Iridium satellites, [[ALOS]] satellite (which can produce flashes up to \u221210 mag), etc.\nThe most important and valuable information about tumbling satellites is a period of flashes. It can vary from 0.3\u20130.5 seconds (rapidly rotating objects) to a minute or more (slowly rotating objects). Other important characteristics are the amplitude of changes in brightness and period of repetition of these changes.\n\n[[Humanity Star]] was a passive satellite which is primarily designed to produce satellite flares.\n\n== Observation ==\n{{main article|List of satellite pass predictors}}\n\nWhile satellites may be seen by chance, there are websites and [[mobile app]]s which provide location specific information as to when and where in the sky a satellite flare may be seen (for controlled satellites), or trajectory of a tumbling satellite's [[pass (spaceflight)|pass]] (for uncontrolled satellites) in the sky.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[NanoSail-D]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* {{URL|https://sourceforge.net/projects/previsat/}} \u2013 PreviSat software which calculates satellite flares (Iridium, MetOp, SkyMed)\n* {{URL|http://www.heavens-above.com/IridiumFlares.aspx}} \u2013 schedule of upcoming Iridium flares\n* {{URL|http://iridiumflares.sourceforge.net}} \u2013 IridiumFlares prediction software (Java application)\n* {{URL|http://satobs.org/iridium.html}} \u2013 \"Catch a Flaring Iridium\" at Visual Satellite Observer\n* {{URL|http://www.fifthstarlabs.com/}} \u2013 SkyGuide\n* {{URL|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ePBE7pHzAdA}} Iridium 25 flare near the Moon\n\n[[Category:Satellites]]\n[[Category:Visibility]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- lead images -->\n{| class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 300px\" \n|-\n|\n{| style=\"background: white; white-space: nowrap;\" cellpadding=0 cellspacing=2\n|-\n| colspan=2 | [[File:Flare Simulation.gif|302px|]]\n|-\n|[[File:Iridium flare 2008 08 11.jpg|x100px|]]&thinsp;[[File:Comet holmes and iridium flare.jpg|x100px|]];[[file:Iridium flare in Cassiopeia.webm|x100px|]]\n|}\n|-\n|\n* Top: a simulated animation of a typical Iridium flare\n* Middle: Both images show a flare of an [[Iridium satellite constellation|Iridium satellite]]. Comet [[17P/Holmes|Holmes]] can be seen in the right image, slightly above the tree branch.\n*Bottom: Video of a flare\n|}\n\n'''Satellite flare''', also known as '''satellite glint''', is a [[Artificial satellite|satellite]] [[pass (spaceflight)|pass]] [[human vision|visible]] to the [[naked eye]] as a brief, bright \"[[flare]]\". It is caused by the reflection toward the Earth below of sunlight incident on satellite surfaces such as [[Photovoltaic module|solar panels]] and [[Antenna (radio)|antennas]] (e.g., [[Synthetic aperture radar|SAR]]).\n\nThe first generation of the [[Iridium satellite constellation|Iridium constellation]] with 66 active telecommunication satellites in [[low Earth orbit]] were known to cause '''Iridium flares''', the brightest flares of all [[Geocentric orbit|orbiting]] satellites. Throughout 2017 and 2018 they are being replaced with a new generation that does not produce flares, with the first generation expected to be completely phased out by late 2018.\n\n== Controlled satellites ==\n[[File:Iridium animation.gif|thumb|Flaring from reflection of the Sun]]\nTime and place of the satellite's flare can be predicted only when the satellite is controlled, and its orientation in space is known. In this case it is possible to predict the exact time of the flare, its place in the sky, the brightness and duration.\n\n=== Iridium flares ===\n[[File:Iridium 6 & 51.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Double flare - Iridium 6 and its replacement, #51, both flare in a 21-second exposure.]]\nIf a first-generation Iridium satellite is still controlled, its flares can be predicted.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Peat|first=Chris|date=2018-05-15|location=[[Munich]]|website=Heavens-Above|url=https://www.heavens-above.com/IridiumDemise.aspx|title=The end of Iridium flares?|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref> The [[Iridium satellite constellation|Iridium communication satellites]] have three polished door-sized antennas, 120\u00b0 apart and at 40\u00b0 angles with the main bus. The forward antenna faces the direction the satellite is traveling. Occasionally, an antenna reflects sunlight directly down at Earth, creating a predictable and quickly moving illuminated spot on the surface below of about {{convert|10|km|abbr=on}} diameter. To an observer this looks like a bright flash, or flare in the sky, with a duration of a few seconds.\n\nRanging up to \u22129.5 [[apparent magnitude|magnitude]], some of the flares are so bright that they can be seen in the daytime. This flashing has caused some annoyance to [[Astronomer#Modern astronomers|astronomers]], as the flares occasionally disturb observations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apollosat.com/iridium-flare-satellite-tracker/|title=Iridium Flare Satellite Tracker|website=Apollo Satellite Communications|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-06}}</ref>\n\nAs the Iridium constellation consists of 66 working satellites, Iridium flares are visible quite often (2\u20134 times per night). Flares of brightness \u22125 magnitude occur 3\u20134 times per week; \u22128 magnitude may be visible 3\u20135 times per month for stationary observers.\n\nFlares may also occur from solar panels, but they are not as bright (up to \u22123.5 magnitude). Such flares last about twice as long as those from the main mission antennas (MMA), because the so-called \"mirror angle\" for the solar panels is twice that for the MMAs. There are also rare cases of flares from MMAs and solar panels, or two MMAs (front and either right or left) of one satellite in a single [[pass (spaceflight)|pass]].\n\nThe flares can be bright enough to be seen at night in big cities where light pollution usually prevents most stellar observation. When not flaring, the satellites are often visible crossing the night sky at a typical magnitude of 6, similar to a dim star.\n\nThroughout 2017 and 2018, a new generation of Iridium satellites is being deployed which does not exhibit the characteristic flares. As the first generation have been replaced and retired, flares have become less frequent. The last of the first-generation satellites are expected to be deorbited in late 2018, ending predictable Iridium flares.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.skyatnightmagazine.com/news/iridium-flares-cease-end-2018|title=Iridium flares to cease by end of 2018|last=Carter |first=Jamie |date=2017-11-14 |website=BBC Sky at Night Magazine|language=en |access-date=2018-05-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Non-Iridium flares ===\n{{noref section|date=June 2018}}\n[[File:COSMO Skymed flare.PNG|thumb|180px|A [[COSMO-SkyMed]] flare]] \n[[File:MetOp-A satellite flare May 26 2019.jpg|thumb|180px|A MetOp-A flare]]\n\nThere are many controlled satellites in addition to Iridium satellites, which can also flare, but most flares of these satellites do not exceed magnitude \u22122, and are therefore often overlooked.\n\n[[MetOp|MetOp-A, B, and C]], however, can produce predictable flares up to \u22125 magnitude. Four [[COSMO-SkyMed]] satellites can produce flares up to \u22124 magnitude, and lasting much longer than the Iridium flares.\n\nThe [[International Space Station]] (ISS) is known to cause bright [[ISS flare]]s.<ref>[https://www.skyandtelescope.com/observing/watch-international-space-station/]</ref><ref>[https://www.universetoday.com/142187/the-international-space-station-rides-high-through-the-may-sky/]</ref><ref>[https://www.space.com/5610-spot-space-station.html]</ref><ref>[https://spotthestation.nasa.gov/]</ref>\n\nPlanned low-orbit satellite constellations such as [[Startlink]] are a concern for the astronomical community because of [[light pollution]].<ref>{{cite web|title=After SpaceX Starlink Launch, a Fear of Satellites That Outnumber All Visible Stars |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/01/science/starlink-spacex-astronomers.html|website=The New York Times|accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The unexpected brightness of new satellites could ruin the night sky|website=The Economist|url=https://www.economist.com/science-and-technology/2019/05/30/the-unexpected-brightness-of-new-satellites-could-ruin-the-night-sky|accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=SpaceX's Starlink Could Change The Night Sky Forever, And Astronomers Are Not Happy|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jonathanocallaghan/2019/05/27/spacexs-starlink-could-change-the-night-sky-forever-and-astronomers-are-not-happy/|website=Forbes|accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Uncontrolled satellites ==\n\nWhen the satellite's orientation goes out of control, it becomes possible to predict only a trajectory of its pass, at any point of which it can flare up. These satellites are also described as \"tumbling\". This category includes a lot of rotating rocket bodies, some failed Iridium satellites, [[ALOS]] satellite (which can produce flashes up to \u221210 mag), etc.\nThe most important and valuable information about tumbling satellites is a period of flashes. It can vary from 0.3\u20130.5 seconds (rapidly rotating objects) to a minute or more (slowly rotating objects). Other important characteristics are the amplitude of changes in brightness and period of repetition of these changes.\n\n[[Humanity Star]] was a passive satellite which is primarily designed to produce satellite flares.\n\n== Observation ==\n{{main article|List of satellite pass predictors}}\n\nWhile satellites may be seen by chance, there are websites and [[mobile app]]s which provide location specific information as to when and where in the sky a satellite flare may be seen (for controlled satellites), or trajectory of a tumbling satellite's [[pass (spaceflight)|pass]] (for uncontrolled satellites) in the sky.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[NanoSail-D]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* {{URL|https://sourceforge.net/projects/previsat/}} \u2013 PreviSat software which calculates satellite flares (Iridium, MetOp, SkyMed)\n* {{URL|http://www.heavens-above.com/IridiumFlares.aspx}} \u2013 schedule of upcoming Iridium flares\n* {{URL|http://iridiumflares.sourceforge.net}} \u2013 IridiumFlares prediction software (Java application)\n* {{URL|http://satobs.org/iridium.html}} \u2013 \"Catch a Flaring Iridium\" at Visual Satellite Observer\n* {{URL|http://www.fifthstarlabs.com/}} \u2013 SkyGuide\n* {{URL|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ePBE7pHzAdA}} Iridium 25 flare near the Moon\n\n[[Category:Satellites]]\n[[Category:Visibility]]\n", "name_user": "Fgnievinski", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNon-Iridium flares", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satellite_flare"}
{"title_page": "Bailey Jay", "text_new": "{{short description|American pornographic actress, model, and podcaster}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Infobox adult biography\n| name = Bailey Jay\n| image = Bailey Jay at AVN Awards 2011 1 (crop).jpg\n| caption = Bailey Jay at the 2011 AVN Awards\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1988|11|5}}<ref name=\"iafd\"/>\n| birth_place = [[Richmond, Virginia]], [[United States]]<ref name=\"iafd\"/>\n| birth_name =\n| spouse = Brad palmer\n| death_date =\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=5}}<ref>{{cite tweet |user=baileyjaytweets |number=731192816290963458 |date=May 13, 2016 |title=I try not to be vain but somebody tell Wikipedia I'm actually only 5'5 lol.}}</ref>{{r|iafd}}\n| weight = {{convert|132|lb|kg|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"About Me\"/>\n| alias = Harley Quinn,<ref name=\"iafd\"/>  Line Trap<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |url=http://news.avn.com/company-news/Ts-Newcomer-Sensation-Bailey-Jay-Launches-Official-Website-398705.html |title=AVN \u2013 TS Newcomer Sensation Bailey Jay Launches Official Website |publisher=News.avn.com |date=2010-06-01 |accessdate=2012-03-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120428015317/http://news.avn.com/company-news/Ts-Newcomer-Sensation-Bailey-Jay-Launches-Official-Website-398705.html |archive-date=2012-04-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| website = {{URL|http://www.ts-baileyjay.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Bailey Jay''' (born November 5, 1988) is an American [[pornographic actress]], [[Fetish model|adult model]], and [[podcaster]].<ref name=\"iafd\">{{cite web|title=Bailey Jay |publisher=IAFD.com |url=http://www.iafd.com/person.rme/perfid=BaileyJay/gender=m/Bailey-Jay.htm |accessdate=2011-02-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101023171749/http://www.iafd.com/person.rme/perfid%3Dbaileyjay/gender%3Dm/bailey-jay.htm |archivedate=2010-10-23 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 2011 and 2012, Jay won the [[AVN Award]] for [[transgender]] performer of the year.<ref name=avn11win>{{cite web  | title =Bailey Jay is AVN Transsexual Performer of the Year | publisher = AVN.com| url =http://business.avn.com/company-news/Superstarlet-BAILEY-JAY-Wins-AVN-Transsexual-Performer-of-the-Year-423222.html | date = 2011-01-14| accessdate = 2011-02-08}}</ref><ref name=avn12win/> She also co-hosts the [[podcast]] ''The Bailey Jay Show'' (formerly ''Bailey Jay Radio'') with her husband, photographer Matthew Terhune, the podcast ''The Trans Witching Hour with Bailey Jay'' (formerly ''Gender Coaching with Bailey Jay'') that deals with spirituality, the horror-themed podcast ''Blood Lust with Bailey Jay'' and also co-hosts the [[transgender]] and [[transsexuality]] advice podcast ''Sugar and Spice'' (formerly ''Third Gender Radio'') with Jen Richards of [[We Happy Trans]].\n\n==Filmography and appearances==\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2014\n| American Dream\n| Mom 2\n| Cary Nokey video\n|}\n\n===Web===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''The [[Jim Norton (American comedian)|Jim Norton]] Show''\n| Co-Host/Announcer\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''NICE TIPS!''\n| Advice columnist\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''The Approval Matrix'' \n| Herself\n| Episode: \"America's Hall Monitors\"\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Inside Amy Schumer]]''\n| Herself\n| Episode: \"Last Fuckable Day\"\n|}\n\n===Podcasts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Title\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2010\u2013present\n| ''The Bailey Jay Show'' (with Matt Terhune)\n| Weekly podcast <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.riotcast.com/baileyjay|title=The Bailey Jay Show|work=riotcast.com|accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Robert Kelly (comedian)|You Know What Dude]]''\n| Two appearances<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.robertkelly.libsyn.com/webpage/2011/11|title=Robert Kelly's 'You Know What Dude!'|work=libsyn.com|accessdate=18 September 201